{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"92336926-59f4-4f9f-8568-db9b4923a6d9","content":"I don't see a `.dmp` file in the current directory. Could you provide the path to your dump file?\n\nIn the meantime, here's how you can analyze a .NET crash dump:\n\n**Using `dotnet-dump` (recommended):**\n```bash\n# Install the tool\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\n\n# Open the dump interactively\ndotnet-dump analyze /path/to/your.dmp\n```\n\n**Useful SOS commands inside the analyzer:**\n| Command | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `clrstack` | Managed call stack of current thread |\n| `pe` (PrintException) | Show last exception details |\n| `dumpheap -stat` | Heap summary (for OOM issues) |\n| `threads` | List all managed threads |\n| `setthread <id>` | Switch to a specific thread |\n| `clrstack -all` | Stacks for all threads |\n\n**Typical workflow:**\n1. `pe` — check if there's an unhandled exception\n2. `threads` — find the faulting thread\n3. `setthread <id>` + `clrstack` — inspect its stack\n4. `dso` (DumpStackObjects) — inspect objects on that frame\n\nIf you share the dump file path or upload it here, I can walk you through the analysis interactively.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"02ace3f8-e4a7-438e-9e94-eb0c9d36e765","outputTokens":318,"requestId":"D7C4:11233D:100795E:126C7F3:69F2B6FA"},"id":"d22dc233-121d-4894-8475-2c7486698c4c","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:57:22.348Z","parentId":"cc0af5eb-3d7d-44b8-82a2-1d30858ef59d"}
